Sure, here's an example implementation of the "divide and conquer" algorithm to find the maximum and minimum values of the given integer array in Java:
```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner input = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter the integer array: ");
        int[] array = readArray(input);

        System.out.println("Using the divide and conquer algorithm to find the minimum and maximum values:");

        int min = minimum(array, 0, array.length - 1);
        int max = maximum(array, 0, array.length - 1);

        System.out.println("The minimum value is: " + min);
        System.out.println("The maximum value is: " + max);
    }

    private static int minimum(int[] array, int start, int end) {
        if (start == end)
            return array[start];

        int mid = (start + end) / 2;
        int leftMin = minimum(array, start, mid);
        int rightMin = minimum(array, mid + 1, end);

        if (leftMin > array[mid])
            return rightMin < array[mid]? rightMin : array[mid];
        else
            return leftMin < array[mid]? leftMin : array[mid];
    }

    private static int maximum(int[] array, int start, int end) {
        if (start == end)
            return array[start];

        int mid = (start + end) / 2;
        int leftMax = maximum(array, start, mid);
        int rightMax = maximum(array, mid + 1, end);

        if (leftMax < array[mid])
            return rightMax > array[mid]? rightMax : array[mid];
        else
            return leftMax > array[mid]? leftMax : array[mid];
    }

    private static int[] readArray(Scanner input) {
        int numberOfElements = input.nextInt();
        int[] array = new int[numberOfElements];
        for (int i = 0; i < numberOfElements; i++)
            array[i] = input.nextInt();
        return array;
    }
}
```
The `main` method reads the integer array from the user input, and then calls the `minimum` and `maximum` methods to find the minimum and maximum values, respectively.

The `minimum` and `maximum` methods use the "divide and conquer" algorithm to recursively split the array in half until they reach the base case (i.e. the length of the subarray is 1), and then compare the elements using a binary search tree approach to find the minimum or maximum value.

The `readArray` method reads the input integer array from a `Scanner` object and returns the array.

Try running the code and provide the input array to see the output with the minimum and maximum values.

