To create this Swift function, you would need to access the Wordnik API for the definition of "alacrity," parse the JSON response, and then generate the formula with missing values filled in. Here is an example Swift function that does just that, using the URLSession API and SwiftJSON library:

```swift
import Foundation
import SwiftyJSON

func alacrityFormula(completion: @escaping (String) -> Void) {
    let apiKey = "YOUR_WORDNIK_API_KEY"
    let urlString = "https://api.wordnik.com/v4/word.json/alacrity/definitions?api_key=\(apiKey)"

    guard let url = URL(string: urlString) else {
        print("Invalid URL")
        return
    }

    let task = URLSession.shared.dataTask(with: url) { data, response, error in
        guard let data = data, error == nil else {
            print("Error in URLSession dataTask")
            return
        }

        do {
            let json = try JSON(data: data)
            guard let wordDefinition = json[0]["text"].string else {
                print("Error retrieving word definition")
                return
            }

            let formula = "A certain \(wordDefinition) was displayed [adjective] in their actions with [plural noun]. What is the word?"
            completion(formula)
        } catch {
            print("Error parsing JSON: \(error)")
        }
    }

    task.resume()
}

alacrityFormula() { formula in
    print(formula)
}
```

Replace `YOUR_WORDNIK_API_KEY` with your actual Wordnik API key. You can get a free API key by registering at the Wordnik developer portal: https://developer.wordnik.com.

Also, make sure you have the SwiftyJSON library installed by adding the following line in your `Package.swift` dependencies:

```swift
.package(url: "https://github.com/SwiftyJSON/SwiftyJSON.git", from: "4.0.0")
```

Keep in mind that due to URLSession being used, this function must be run in an environment with networking capabilities (for example, on iOS or macOS apps). It will not work in the Swift Playground.

