In Java, to calculate the motion of an object when we know its initial position, velocity, and the force acting upon it, we can use the concept of calculus and the second law of motion. The second law of motion states that the acceleration of an object is directly proportional to the force applied on the object and inversely proportional to the mass of the object.

To demonstrate this law in Java, we can create a simple example program that calculates the motion of a ball falling from a height. Here's an example code snippet:
```java
double gravity = 9.8; // acceleration due to gravity in m/s^2
double mass = 0.1; // mass of the ball in kg
double x0 = 0; // initial position of the ball in m
double v0 = 0; // initial velocity of the ball in m/s
double t = 0; // time in seconds

// update the velocity and position of the ball every 0.01 seconds
while (t <= 10) {
  double a = gravity * mass; // acceleration
  double v = v0 + a * t; // velocity
  double x = x0 + v * t; // position

  // print the position and velocity of the ball
  System.out.printf("At time %2.4f: position = %2.4f m, velocity = %2.4f m/s\n", t, x, v);

  // update the time and velocity
  t += 0.01;
  v0 += a * t;
}
```
This program calculates the position and velocity of a ball as it falls from a starting position of `(x0, 0)` with initial velocity `v0` and updates its position and velocity every 0.01 seconds. The force acting on the ball is the acceleration due to gravity `gravity * mass`. The resulting acceleration `a` is added to the initial velocity `v0` to calculate the new velocity at each time step and the new position of the ball is calculated by multiplying the velocity by the time elapsed.

This example uses the second law of motion to calculate the motion of the ball and demonstrate how the force acting on an object affects its acceleration and motion.

