I would recommend using a one-pass algorithm that keeps track of the largest and second largest elements in the array. This approach has a time complexity of O(n) where n is the number of elements in the array. Here's a C++ function named `secondLargest` that implements this approach:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <limits>

int secondLargest(const std::vector<int>& arr) {
    // Check if the array has less than two elements
    if (arr.size() < 2) {
        throw std::invalid_argument("Array must have at least two elements");
    }

    int largest = std::numeric_limits<int>::min();
    int secondLargest = std::numeric_limits<int>::min();

    for (const int& num : arr) {
        if (num > largest) {
            secondLargest = largest;
            largest = num;
        } else if (num > secondLargest && num < largest) {
            secondLargest = num;
        }
    }

    return secondLargest;
}

int main() {
    std::vector<int> arr = {10, 20, 4, 30, 2};
    try {
        int result = secondLargest(arr);
        std::cout << "The second largest element is " << result << std::endl;
    } catch(const std::exception& e) {
        std::cerr << e.what() << std::endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

This code first initializes `largest` and `secondLargest` to the lowest possible integer value. It then iterates through the input array, updating `largest` and `secondLargest` accordingly. If an element has a higher value than the current largest, the algorithm updates `secondLargest` to the current `largest` value and `largest` to the new highest value. If an element is greater than `secondLargest` but less than `largest`, it only updates `secondLargest`.

Note that the function throws an exception if the array has less than two elements, as a second largest element cannot be determined in such cases.

